{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5957c292-2411-4e81-bf07-f85a072eea70","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file in the current directory.\n\n### 5. Copy the trace out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\nThen view at [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app).\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet-trace` can't attach (common in some Windows container images), use `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first to confirm diagnostics are working. If not, set `DOTNET_EnableDiagnostics=1` and restart the app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"27d54e54-9aaf-4603-a999-800e5fc09c0c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":449,"requestId":"4043:A917E:70E3F2B:7CA33EE:69F15DA2"},"id":"a8afbaee-643b-4a8d-b156-fb3c2ece2ed3","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:23:56.970Z","parentId":"21f90b62-96d1-4545-850d-1fbe37b2acee"}
